├── data/ (created automatically)
│ ├── students.dat
│ ├── courses.dat
│ ├── enrollments.dat
│ ├── grades.dat
│ └── attendance.dat
└── README.md

text

**Note:** The code uses package `studentManagementSystemGUI`. Compile and run as shown below.

## 🚀 How to Compile & Run

### From the command line (inside `student-management-gui/` folder):

```bash
# Compile
javac src/studentManagementSystemGUI/StudentManagementSystemGUI.java

# Run
java -cp src studentManagementSystemGUI.StudentManagementSystemGUI
Alternative (if you prefer to run from the root of the project):
bash
javac src/studentManagementSystemGUI/*.java
java -cp src studentManagementSystemGUI.StudentManagementSystemGUI
Using an IDE (Eclipse, IntelliJ, NetBeans)
Import the src folder as source root.

Run StudentManagementSystemGUI.main(...).

📝 Usage Walkthrough
Students tab – Add students with unique ID. Select a row to update/delete.

Courses tab – Add courses. Credits must be 1–6.

Enrollment tab – Choose a student and a course, click Enroll. Withdraw by selecting a row.

Grades tab – Select a student, then a course they are enrolled in, assign a grade.

Attendance tab – Set attendance percentage (0–100) for a student in a specific course.

Reports tab – Generate any report and export to CSV (saved in data/ folder).

🔒 Security & Data Integrity
No SQL injection – uses only in‑memory collections + serialisation.

Input validation – age (0–150), credits (1–6), attendance (0–100), grade format.

Duplicate prevention – student ID and course code must be unique.

Referential integrity – deleting a student removes all enrollments, grades, attendance.

Serialisation – data is stored in binary format (not human‑editable, but safe from casual tampering).

⚠️ Known Limitations & Future Improvements
Serialisation format – not portable across different Java versions if classes change. Consider JSON or SQLite for production.

No authentication – single‑user only. Add login for multiple roles.

No backup/restore – manually copy data/ folder.

Attendance tracking – only a single percentage per student‑course (no per‑date records).

Possible enhancements:

Use JCalendar for date‑specific attendance.

Add a grade point average (GPA) chart.

Integrate with a database (H2, MySQL).

